\f3\s+2Casida de las palomas oscuras\s0\fP
.sp 0.4c
.IP \  4.5c
Por las ramas del laurel
.br
van dos palomas oscuras.
.br
La una era el sol,
.br
la otra la luna.
.br
`Vecinitas' les dije,
.br
`\*? dónde está mi sepultura ?'
.br
`En mi cola' dijó el sol.
.br
`En mi garganta', dijo la luna.
.br
Y yo que estaba caminando
.br
con la terra por la cintura
.br
vi dos águilas de nieve
.br
y una muchacha desnuda.
.br
La una era la otra
.br
y la muchacha era ninguna.
.br
`Aguilitas' les dije,
.br
`\*? dónde está mi sepultura ?'
.br
`En mi cola' dijó el sol.
.br
`En mi garganta', dijo la luna.
.br
Por las ramas del laurel
.br
vi dos palomas desnudas.
.br
La una era la otra
.br
y las dos eran ninguna.
.sp 0.7c
.IP \  8c
\f3Federico\ García\ Lorca\fP
.sp 1.6c
.IP \  2.0c
Federico García Lorca's last collection of poems,
\f2Diván del Tamarit\fP,
was written in 1934 and
would have been published in 1936 by the University of Granada
had not the Civil War intervened;
it was published posthumously by Colombia University in 1940.
\f2Diván\fP is an Arabic word
meaning the poet's collected verse,
generally arranged in alphabetical order of the rhymes.
\f2Tamarit\fP was the name of a \f2huerta\fP, or small farm,
which belonged to the father of one of Lorca's favourite cousins
and enjoyed wonderful views of the Sierra Nevada and the plain of the Vega;
\f2tamarit\fP is also an Arabic word, meaning "abundant in dates".

.IP \  2.0c
\f2Diván del Tamarit\fP consists of twelve \f2Gacelas\fP
and nine \f2Casidas\fP; 
\f2Gacela\fP derives from the Persian \f2ghazal\fP,
meaning a short love poem,
and \f2Casida\fP derives from the Arabic \f2qasida\fP,
meaning a longer poem with a particular structure featuring a single rhyme.

.IP \  2.0c
.nh
These are \f2Casidas\fP numbers \f2II\fP, \f2VII\fP, and \f2IX\fP.
The translations on page 20 are by the composer.
The setting offered here is a 2005 revision of the original 1997 composition.
